            <abstract>
                <p>Magic prayer and prescription. The title words are taken from the incipit as presented in
                    <bibl><ptr target="bm:Strelcyn1978BritishLibrary"/><citedRange unit="page">151</citedRange></bibl> and seem to be
                    ʾasmāt, possibly derived from Coptic-Arabic months or Arabic zodiacal signs, e.g.: 
                    <foreign xml:lang="gez">ባብ፡</foreign>, cf. arab. <foreign xml:lang="ar">bāba</foreign> (2nd month of the Coptic calender);
                    <foreign xml:lang="gez">አብደድ፡</foreign>, cf. arab. <foreign xml:lang="ar">ʿabd</foreign> 'servant', possibly also with an 
                    astrological meaning or category;
                    <foreign xml:lang="gez">ሑጢ፡</foreign>, cf. arab. <foreign xml:lang="ar">al-ḥūt</foreign> being a sign of the zodiac (Pisces).
                    According to <bibl><ptr target="bm:Strelcyn1978BritishLibrary"/><citedRange unit="page">144-153</citedRange></bibl>, 
                    prayer and prescription 'that acts as an aphrodisiac'.</p>
            </abstract>
